{
  "local_port": 50684,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are famous places in Rajasthan?",
  "response": "Rajasthan, known as the \"Land of Kings,\" is a state in northern India renowned for its rich history, vibrant culture, and stunning architecture. Here are some famous places to visit in Rajasthan:\n\n1. **Jaipur (The Pink City)**\n   - **Hawa Mahal**: A palace known for its unique beehive-like structure with 953 small windows.\n   - **City Palace**: A historic palace complex that now serves as a museum and royal residence.\n   - **Amber Fort**: A majestic fort located on a hilltop overlooking Maota Lake.\n   - **Jantar Mantar**: An astronomical observatory with the world's largest stone sundial.\n\n2. **Udaipur (The City of Lakes)**\n   - **Lake Palace**: A luxurious palace turned hotel located on Lake Pichola.\n   - **City Palace**: A magnificent palace complex with a blend of Rajasthani and Mughal architecture.\n   - **Saheliyon Ki Bari**: A beautiful garden with fountains and kiosks, built for royal ladies.\n\n3. **Jodhpur (The Blue City)**\n   - **Mehrangarh Fort**: A formidable fort that offers stunning views of the city.\n   - **Jaswant Thada**: A beautiful marble cenotaph built in memory of Maharaja Jaswant Singh II.\n   - **Umaid Bhawan Palace**: A grand palace that now serves as a museum and luxury hotel.\n\n4. **Jaisalmer (The Golden City)**\n   - **Jaisalmer Fort**: Also known as Sonar Quila, this fort is made entirely of yellow sandstone.\n   - **Patwon Ki Haveli**: A cluster of five havelis known for their intricate architecture.\n   - **Sam Sand Dunes**: Famous for desert safaris and camel rides.\n\n5. **Pushkar**\n   - **Pushkar Lake**: A sacred lake surrounded by 52 ghats where pilgrims bathe.\n   - **Brahma Temple**: One of the few temples dedicated to Lord Brahma in the world.\n   - **Pushkar Camel Fair**: An annual fair that attracts thousands of visitors with its vibrant cultural activities.\n\n6. **Ranthambore National Park**\n   - Known for its tiger population and diverse wildlife, this park offers excellent opportunities for safaris.\n\n7. **Ajmer**\n   - **Ajmer Sharif Dargah**: The shrine of the Sufi saint Moinuddin Chishti, attracting pilgrims from across the world.\n   - **Taragarh Fort**: An ancient hill fort with panoramic views of Ajmer.\n\n8. **Bikaner**\n   - **Junagarh Fort**: A well-preserved fort with beautiful palaces and temples inside.\n   - **Lalgarh Palace**: A red sandstone palace that now serves as a museum and heritage hotel.\n   - **Karni Mata Temple (Rat Temple)**: A unique temple dedicated to Karni Mata, where rats are considered sacred.\n\n9. **Chittorgarh**\n   - **Chittorgarh Fort**: One of the largest forts in India, known for its historical significance and grand architecture.\n   - **Vijay Stambh (Victory Tower)**: A towering monument celebrating a victory over the Malwa Sultanate.\n\n10. **Mount Abu**\n    - **Dilwara Temples**: A complex of Jain temples known for their intricate marble carvings.\n    - **Nakki Lake**: A scenic lake surrounded by hills and ideal for boating.\n    - **Sunset Point**: A popular spot to enjoy breathtaking sunset views.\n\nThese destinations showcase the diverse beauty and heritage of Rajasthan, making it a must-visit region for travelers interested in history, culture, and natural beauty.",
  "response_tokens": [
